<div class="info-section" slot="info">
<h2>ASCII Art Generator - Convert Text to ASCII Art Online</h2>
    <p>The ASCII Art Generator converts any text into creative ASCII art using a variety of fonts and styles. Whether you want to create banners, headers, or fun text art for terminals, chat messages, or code comments, this tool makes it fast and easy. Just type your text, pick a font, and your ASCII art is ready to copy or download instantly.</p>

    <h3>What Is ASCII Art?</h3>
    <p>ASCII art is a graphic design technique that uses printable characters from the ASCII (American Standard Code for Information Interchange) character set to create visual designs and text-based images. It originated in the early days of computing when graphical displays were not available, and programmers used characters like #, *, |, and / to draw pictures and decorative text in terminals and printers.</p>
    <p>Despite the widespread availability of modern graphics, ASCII art remains popular today for a variety of reasons. It works in any environment that can display plain text — from terminal emulators and command-line interfaces to README files, chat applications, and email. It has a distinctive retro aesthetic that many developers and designers appreciate for its nostalgic charm and technical character.</p>
    <p>Modern ASCII art has evolved beyond simple character drawings to include elaborate multi-line text banners using Unicode block characters, which produce much sharper and more visually impressive results than traditional ASCII alone. Our generator supports both classic ASCII styles and modern Unicode-enhanced fonts for maximum visual impact.</p>

    <h3>ASCII Art Styles and Options</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Multiple font styles including Standard, Banner, Block, Bubble, Digital, and Slant for diverse visual outputs.</li>
        <li>Real-time preview that updates as you type, so you can see your ASCII art take shape instantly.</li>
        <li>One-click copy button to copy the generated art to your clipboard for immediate use anywhere.</li>
        <li>Download as .txt option to save your ASCII art as a plain text file for later use.</li>
        <li>Support for letters, numbers, and common punctuation characters across all font styles.</li>
        <li>Completely browser-based with no server calls, ensuring fast performance and full privacy.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How to Use the ASCII Art Generator</h3>
    <p>Generating ASCII art with this tool is quick and straightforward — no technical knowledge required.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Step 1: Type your desired text into the input field. Keep it short (under 15 characters) for the best visual results, as longer text can become very wide.</li>
        <li>Step 2: Select a font style from the dropdown menu. Try different styles to see which one fits your use case — Block for bold impact, Slant for a dynamic look, or Standard for a clean classic style.</li>
        <li>Step 3: The ASCII art preview updates automatically as you type and change fonts, so you can experiment freely.</li>
        <li>Step 4: Once you are happy with the result, click the Copy button to copy the art to your clipboard.</li>
        <li>Step 5: Paste the ASCII art wherever you need it — a README file, a code comment, a terminal, a chat message, or anywhere else that accepts plain text.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Creative Uses for ASCII Art</h3>
    <p>ASCII art has a surprisingly wide range of practical and creative applications in the modern world.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>README files — add stylish, eye-catching headers to GitHub or GitLab README files to make your project stand out.</li>
        <li>Code comments — mark major sections of a codebase with decorative banners to improve navigation and readability.</li>
        <li>Terminal applications — create splash screens, welcome messages, and section dividers for CLI tools and scripts.</li>
        <li>Social media bios — add a creative, unique touch to your profile bio on platforms that support plain text formatting.</li>
        <li>Email signatures — include a distinctive ASCII art signature in your emails for a memorable personal brand.</li>
        <li>Game development — create retro-style title screens, menus, and UI elements for text-based or terminal games.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Crafting Better ASCII Art</h3>
    <p>For the best visual results, keep your input text short — ideally five to ten characters. Longer strings produce very wide output that may not display correctly in environments with limited line width, such as terminals set to 80 columns. If you need to display a longer phrase, consider breaking it into multiple lines and generating each line separately.</p>
    <p>Always view your ASCII art in a monospace font before using it. Most terminals, code editors, and README renderers use monospace fonts by default, which is essential for ASCII art to align correctly. If you paste ASCII art into a proportional-font environment like a word processor or email client, the characters will not line up and the art will look broken.</p>
    <p>When using ASCII art in code comments, wrap it in a block comment style appropriate for your language. In JavaScript or CSS, use /* ... */, and in Python, use triple quotes or # prefixes on each line. This ensures the art is treated as a comment and does not affect code execution.</p>

    

    <h3>No Files Uploaded — All Local</h3>
    <p>All rendering runs in your browser. Your text never leaves your device.</p>

            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What fonts are available for ASCII art?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>The generator includes a variety of ASCII art fonts ranging from simple block letters to decorative styles. Each font uses different ASCII characters to form the letters, giving each a unique visual style.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I use ASCII art in emails or chat apps?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes, as long as the destination uses a monospace font. ASCII art relies on fixed-width characters to align properly. In apps that use proportional fonts (like most email clients), the art may look misaligned. Use it in terminals, code comments, or plain-text environments for best results.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the maximum text length for ASCII art?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Shorter text works best. Long words or sentences can produce very wide output that wraps awkwardly. For best results, keep input to a single word or short phrase. You can generate multiple lines separately and combine them.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why does my ASCII art look different when I paste it?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>ASCII art must be viewed in a monospace font to look correct. If you paste it into a document or app using a proportional font, the spacing will be off. Use a code block or preformatted text element to preserve the monospace rendering.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I use ASCII art in my code?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Absolutely. ASCII art is commonly used in code comments for section headers, banners, or decorative separators. Just wrap it in a comment block appropriate for your language (/* */ for CSS/JS, # for Python, -- for SQL).</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>

